the slower they go, planes are already almost as energy-efficient as they could possibly be. Planes unavoidably have to use energy for two reasons: they have to throw air down in order to stay up, and they need energy to overcome air resistance. No redesign of a plane is going to radically improve its efficiency. ",mdx("sup",e({parentName:"p"},{id:"fnref-2"}),mdx("a",e({parentName:"sup"},{href:"#fn-2",className:"footnote-ref"}),"2"))," A 10% improvement? Yes, possible. A doubling of efficiency? I\u2019d eat my complimentary socks."),mdx("h2",e({},{id:"queries"}),"Queries"),mdx("p",null,"Energy per distance (kWh per 100 p-km)"),mdx("p",null,"Car (4 occupants)"),mdx("p",null,"20"),mdx("p",null,"Ryanair\u2019s planes, year 2007"),mdx("p",null,"37"),mdx("p",null,"Bombardier Q400, full"),mdx("p",null,"38"),mdx("p",null,"747, full"),mdx("p",null,"42"),mdx("p",null,"747, 80% full"),mdx("p",null,"53"),mdx("p",null,"Ryanair's planes, year 2000"),mdx("p",null,"73"),mdx("p",null,"Car (1 occupant)"),mdx("p",null,"80"),mdx("span",{class:"figurenumber"},"Table 5.3.")," Passenger transport efficiencies, expressed as energy required per 100 passenger-km.",mdx("h4",e({},{id:"arent-span-idturbopropturboprop-aircraftspan-far-more-energy-efficient"}),"Aren\u2019t ",mdx("span",{id:"turboprop"},"turboprop aircraft")," far more energy-efficient?"),mdx("p",null,'No. The "comfortably greener" Bombardier Q400 NextGen, "the most technologically advanced turboprop in the world," according to its ',mdx("span",{id:"page36"},"manufacturers")," [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"p"},{href:"http://www.q400nextgen.com"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"www.q400.com")),"], uses 3.81 litres per 100 passenger-km (at a cruise speed of 667 km/h), which is an energy cost of ",mdx("span",{class:"mauve"},"38 kWh per 100 p-km"),". The full 747 has an energy cost of ",mdx("span",{class:"mauve"},"42 kWh per 100 p-km"),". So both planes are twice as fuel-efficient as a single-occupancy car. (The car I\u2019m assuming here is the average European car that we discussed in Chapter 3.)"),mdx("h4",e({},{id:"is-flying-extra-bad-for-climate-change-in-some-way"}),"Is flying extra-bad for climate change in some way?"),mdx("p",null,"Yes, that\u2019s the experts\u2019 view, though uncertainty remains about this topic [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"p"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/3fbufz"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"3fbufz")),"]. Flying creates other greenhouse gases in addition to CO",mdx("sub",null,"2"),", such as water and ozone, and indirect greenhouse gases, such as nitrous oxides. If you want to estimate your carbon footprint in tons of CO",mdx("sub",null,"2"),"equivalent, then you should take the actual CO",mdx("sub",null,"2")," emissions of your flights and bump them up two- or three-fold. This book\u2019s diagrams don\u2019t include that multiplier because here we are focusing on our ",mdx("em",{parentName:"p"},"energy")," balance sheet."),mdx("blockquote",null,mdx("p",{parentName:"blockquote"},mdx("em",{parentName:"p"},"The best thing we can do with environmentalists is shoot them.")),mdx("p",{parentName:"blockquote"},"Michael O\u2019Leary, CEO of Ryanair [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"p"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/3asmgy"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"3asmgy")),"]")),mdx("h2",e({},{id:"notes-and-further-reading"}),"Notes and further reading"),mdx("p",null,mdx("img",e({parentName:"p"},{src:"/img/without-hot-air/figure31.gif",alt:null}))),mdx("span",{class:"figurenumber"},"Figure 5.4.")," Ryanair Boeing 737-800. Photograph by Adrian Pingstone.",mdx("p",null,'What about short-haul flights? In 2007, Ryanair, "Europe\u2019s greenest airline," delivered transportation at a cost of ',mdx("span",{class:"darkred"},"37 kWh per 100 p-km")," [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"p"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/3exmgv"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"3exmgv")),"]. This means that flying across Europe with Ryanair has much the same energy cost as having all the passengers drive to their destination in cars, two to a car. (For an indication of what other airlines might be delivering, Ryanair\u2019s fuel burn rate in 2000, before their environment-friendly investments, was above ",mdx("span",{class:"darkred"},"73 kWh per 100 p-km"),".) London to Rome is 1430 km; London to Malaga is 1735 km. So a round-trip to Rome with the greenest airline has an energy cost of 1050 kWh, and a round-trip to Malaga costs 1270 kWh. If you pop over to Rome and to Malaga once per year, your average power consumption is 6.3 kWh/d with the greenest airline, and perhaps 12 kWh/d with a less green one."),mdx("p",null,"What about frequent flyers? To get a silver frequent flyer card from an intercontinental airline, it seems one must fly around 25 000 miles per year in economy class. That\u2019s about 60 kWh per day, if we scale up the opening numbers from this chapter and assume planes are 80% full."),mdx("p",null,"Here are some additional figures from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"p"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/yrnmum"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"yrnmum")),"]: a full 747-400 travelling 10 000 km with low-density seating (262 seats) has an energy consumption of ",mdx("span",{class:"darkred"},"50 kWh per 100 p-km"),". In a high-density seating configuration (568 seats) and travelling 4000 km, the ",mdx("span",{id:"page37"},"same plane")," has an energy consumption of ",mdx("span",{class:"darkred"},"22 kWh per 100 p-km"),". A shorthaul Tupolev-154 travelling 2235 km with 70% of its 164 seats occupied consumes ",mdx("span",{class:"darkred"},"80 kWh per 100 p-km"),"."),mdx("p",null,mdx("img",e({parentName:"p"},{src:"/img/without-hot-air/figure32.gif",alt:null}))),mdx("span",{class:"figurenumber"},"Figure 5.5.")," Two short-haul trips on the greenest short-haul airline: 6.3 kWh/d. Flying enough to qualify for silver frequent flyer status: 60 kWh/d.",mdx("div",e({},{className:"footnotes"}),mdx("hr",{parentName:"div"}),mdx("ol",{parentName:"div"},mdx("li",e({parentName:"ol"},{id:"fn-1"}),mdx("em",{parentName:"li"},"Boeing 747-400")," \u2013 data are from [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"li"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/9ehws"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"9ehws")),"]. Planes today are not completely full. Airlines are proud if their average fullness is 80%. Easyjet planes are 85% full on average. (Source: ",mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"thelondonpaper")," Tuesday 16th January, 2007.) An 80%-full 747 uses about 53 kWh per 100 passenger-km.",mdx("a",e({parentName:"li"},{href:"#fnref-1",className:"footnote-backref"}),"\u21A9")),mdx("li",e({parentName:"ol"},{id:"fn-2"}),mdx("em",{parentName:"li"},mdx("span",{id:"note35"},"No redesign")," of a plane is going to radically improve its efficiency.")," Actually, the Advisory Council for Aerospace Research in Europe (ACARE) target is for an overall 50% reduction in fuel burned per passenger-km by 2020 (relative to a 2000 baseline), with 15\u201320% improvement expected in engine efficiency. As of 2006, Rolls Royce is half way to this engine target [",mdx("a",e({parentName:"li"},{href:"http://tinyurl.com/36w5gz"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"36w5gz")),']. Dennis Bushnell, chief scientist at NASA\u2019s Langley Research Center, seems to agree with my overall assessment of prospects for efficiency improvements in aviation. The aviation industry is mature. "There is not much left to gain except by the glacial accretion of a per cent here and there over long time periods." (New Scientist, 24 February 2007, page 33.) The radically reshaped "Silent Aircraft" [',mdx("a",e({parentName:"li"},{href:"http://silentaircraft.org/sax40"}),mdx("span",{class:"websitetitle"},"silentaircraft.org/sax40")),"], if it were built, is predicted to be 16% more efficient than a conventional-shaped plane (Nickol, 2008). If the ACARE target is reached, it\u2019s presumably going to be thanks mostly to having fuller planes and better air-traffic management.",mdx("a",e({parentName:"li"}